<p>Nevada's economy is one of the most concentrated in the United States around a single industry: gaming and hospitality. Las Vegas is home to the largest casino resort corridor in the world, with MGM Grand, Caesars Entertainment, Wynn Resorts, Las Vegas Sands, and dozens of other operators employing hundreds of thousands of workers across the Strip, Downtown, and extending outward to locals' casinos like the Station and Boyd Gaming properties. Beyond gaming, Nevada has seen significant growth in Reno's technology sector (fueled by Tesla's Gigafactory, Google's data center, and Apple's server farm in the desert), mining operations for gold and lithium, and an enormous logistics industry centered on Las Vegas's position as a distribution hub for the Southwest.</p>

<p>Nevada has no personal income tax -- one of nine states with this distinction. However, Nevada has a mandatory pay stub requirement under state law, making it unusual among no-tax states in requiring written wage statements. This generator calculates all federal deductions and produces a professional, legally compliant Nevada pay stub PDF.</p>

<h2>Nevada Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Nevada has a 0% personal income tax. The Nevada Constitution prohibits an income tax, making this protection exceptionally durable. Nevada funds its state government primarily through the Modified Business Tax (a payroll tax on employers), the gaming license tax, sales tax (6.85% state, up to 8.375% with local additions), and various tourism-related levies.</p>

<p>On a Nevada pay stub, you will see no state income tax withholding. Deductions are limited to:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Federal income tax:</strong> Calculated using IRS graduated brackets (10% to 37%)</li>
  <li><strong>Social Security:</strong> 6.2% up to the $168,600 wage base (2024)</li>
  <li><strong>Medicare:</strong> 1.45% of all wages, plus 0.9% additional for wages over $200,000 annually</li>
  <li><strong>Voluntary deductions:</strong> Health insurance, 401(k), union dues (Culinary Workers Union 226 is one of the largest union locals in the US), etc.</li>
</ul>

<p>Nevada does have an Industrial Insurance (workers' compensation) premium, but this is entirely an employer cost -- it does not appear as an employee payroll deduction. Nevada also does not have state disability insurance or paid family leave deductions.</p>

<h2>Does Nevada Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Yes. Nevada is unusual among no-income-tax states in that it requires pay stubs by law. Nevada Revised Statute (NRS) 608.115 mandates that employers provide employees with a written itemized statement of all deductions made from wages at the time wages are paid.</p>

<p>This requirement makes Nevada's pay stub law stricter than states like Texas or Florida (which have no such mandate) despite Nevada's otherwise business-friendly regulatory environment. The gaming industry's history of complex compensation structures, tip reporting requirements, and union contract compliance likely drove this statutory requirement.</p>

<p>Violations of NRS 608.115 can be reported to the Nevada Labor Commissioner, who can investigate and order compliance.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Nevada</h2>

<p>Under NRS 608.115, a Nevada pay stub must include an itemized statement of all deductions from wages. Combined with standard practice, a complete Nevada pay stub should include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employer name and address</li>
  <li>Employee name</li>
  <li>Pay period start and end dates</li>
  <li>Pay date</li>
  <li>Hours worked (especially important for casino workers with irregular schedules)</li>
  <li>Gross wages (including any tips allocated per the employer tip pooling arrangement)</li>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security and Medicare withheld</li>
  <li>Union dues (where applicable)</li>
  <li>Health insurance premiums</li>
  <li>Any other deductions</li>
  <li>Net wages paid</li>
</ul>

<p>For tip-reporting compliance, many Nevada casino and restaurant employers also show tip allocations and tip credits on pay stubs, though the complexity of tip reporting in Nevada's gaming environment is a specialized topic.</p>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Nevada</h2>

<p>Nevada Revised Statute 608.060 requires that wages be paid at least semi-monthly (twice per month). The paydays must be set in advance and wages must be paid within 15 days of the end of the pay period in which they were earned.</p>

<p>The semi-monthly requirement applies to most Nevada workers. Commission-based employees may have different arrangements if the commissions are calculable only monthly. Most casino employees on hourly wages are paid bi-weekly, which satisfies the semi-monthly minimum.</p>

<p>Final paycheck rules in Nevada are specific: if an employer terminates an employee, the final check must be paid within 3 days of the termination date. If an employee resigns with fewer than 3 days' notice, final payment is due on the next regular payday. If resignation notice was given 3 or more days before the last day of work, the final check is due on the last day of work.</p>

